Treehugging Study - Results

Scott Claessens

2022-08-08

This document reports the results of multilevel models analysing the distribution of treehugging (i.e.valuing nature more than humans) around the world.

We can plot this variable on a global map.

Intercept-only models

First, we fit a standard random intercept multilevel model with treehugging as the outcome variable and random intercepts for countries and study waves.

##  Family: gaussian 
##   Links: mu = identity; sigma = identity 
## Formula: Treehugging ~ 1 + (1 | year) + (1 | iso) 
##    Data: d (Number of observations: 541676) 
##   Draws: 4 chains, each with iter = 4000; warmup = 2000; thin = 1;
##          total post-warmup draws = 8000

We can get intra-class correlations for countries (iso) and study waves (year). The ICC for year is basically 0, meaning there is no variation in the outcome variable across study waves.

## Hypothesis Tests for class :
##                 Hypothesis Estimate Est.Error CI.Lower CI.Upper Evid.Ratio Post.Prob Star
## 1 (sd_year__Interce... = 0        0         0        0     0.01         NA        NA    *
## ---
## 'CI': 90%-CI for one-sided and 95%-CI for two-sided hypotheses.
## '*': For one-sided hypotheses, the posterior probability exceeds 95%;
## for two-sided hypotheses, the value tested against lies outside the 95%-CI.
## Posterior probabilities of point hypotheses assume equal prior probabilities.

The ICC for iso is 0.06, meaning that 6% of the variation in treehugging is between countries.

## Hypothesis Tests for class :
##                 Hypothesis Estimate Est.Error CI.Lower CI.Upper Evid.Ratio Post.Prob Star
## 1 (sd_iso__Intercep... = 0     0.06      0.01     0.04     0.08         NA        NA    *
## ---
## 'CI': 90%-CI for one-sided and 95%-CI for two-sided hypotheses.
## '*': For one-sided hypotheses, the posterior probability exceeds 95%;
## for two-sided hypotheses, the value tested against lies outside the 95%-CI.
## Posterior probabilities of point hypotheses assume equal prior probabilities.

These ICC results mean that in future models we should retain country-level random intercepts, but not study wave random intercepts.

In an additional random intercept model, we can fit another model to determine the proportion of country-level variance that can be explained by geographic and cultural proximity.

75% of the country-level variance can be explained by geographic proximity, while 15% can be explained by linguistic proximity. The additional 10% is explained by neither.

Human Development Index (HDI)

We then fit a model that includes HDI as a standardised country-level predictor, controlling for individual-level demographics. The outcome variable Treehugging is left on the raw data scale (min = -5, max = 5).

There is a small positive effect of HDI. As HDI increases by one standard deviation, the outcome variable increases by 0.08. We can visualise this effect.

Does this effect hold when controlling for geographic and cultural proximity between countries?

Does this effect hold when controlling for geographic and cultural proximity?
